<p>The production and experience of the presence progress into artificial multimodal narratives where distinctions of reality and fiction are irreversibly undermined. Gumbrecht marks in his insightful essay on sports, arts and aesthetics what makes sports i.e. plays so compelling and analogous to arts: itâ€™s a zoom in the original emerging of forms, capable of captivating the attention as we are challenged to recognize the modalities in which these forms eventuate. This creates tensions, resolutions and surprises, structuring attention in particular ways and becoming more and more compelling as the performance has the potential to enfold its observers. Thus an act observed from a distance can progress into a collective effervescence by experiencing â€œthe logic of the distinctions drawn and the operations performed as oneâ€™s ownâ€Î³. Letâ€™s Play builds real states of affectedness in intangible environments, occupied by potential infomorphed life-machine-thingy forms.</p>

